🧩 1) Configure Your Git User Information
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"


✅ Explanation:
Sets your identity so Git can record who made the commits.
Use --global to apply this setting to all repositories on your system.

📥 2) Clone the Repository
git clone https://github.com/<username>/<repository-name>.git


✅ Explanation:
Copies (downloads) a GitHub repository to your local computer.

✍️ 3) Edit the README.txt File

Open the file:

notepad README.txt


(or use VS Code: code README.txt)

Add your name under contributors or anywhere appropriate.

Save and close the file.

🔍 4) Check the Status of Your Repository
git status


✅ Explanation:
Shows which files have been modified, added, or are ready to commit.

📦 5) Stage the Changes
git add README.txt


✅ Explanation:
Marks README.txt to be included in the next commit.

🧾 6) Commit Your Changes
git commit -m "Added my name to contributors list in README.txt"


✅ Explanation:
Saves your staged changes in the local repository with a descriptive message.

☁️ 7) Push Your Changes to the Remote Repository
git push origin main


✅ Explanation:
Uploads your committed changes to the main branch of your GitHub repository.

(If branch is master, use git push origin master.)

🌿 8) Create and Switch to a New Branch
git checkout -b feature/add-my-name


✅ Explanation:
Creates a new branch called feature/add-my-name and switches to it.

📜 9) Demonstrate the git log Command
git log


